label: H1
text: 1. Introduction to the Foundation Level Extensions

label: Body
text: This overview document is intended for anyone with an interest in the ISTQB Foundation Level

label: Body
text: Extensions who wants a high-level introduction to the leading principles and an overview of the individual

label: Body
text: From time to time, ISTQB will update this document to reflect any additional extensions that shall be

label: Body
text: introduced for the Foundation Level, or to reflect major changes in existing ones. Publications of the

label: Body
text: updated document will be available on the ISTQB website.

label: Body
text: The ISTQB Foundation and Advanced Level syllabi have been defined and have been on the market for

label: Body
text: some time. New topics emerge due to technology and methodology changes in the market which often

label: Body
text: are brought into the ISTQB program as new Expert Level syllabi. However, not all topics are suited for the

label: Body
text: Expert Level. For this reason, the extension syllabi are established at the Foundation Level to expand the

label: Body
text: ISTQB program to incorporate new or updated knowledge. New extensions shall be discussed and

label: Body
text: introduced by the ISTQB periodically. Extensions may be established at the Advanced Level as well, but

label: Body
text: that is beyond the scope of this document.

label: Body
text: The following Foundation Level Extension syllabus has been released:

label: Body
text: In this document, each Foundation Level Extension syllabus is summarized and the associated Business

label: Body
text: Outcomes are stated. The Business Outcomes communicate what can be expected from a person who

label: Body
text: achieves a Foundation Level Extension Certification in a particular subject area (e.g., Agile Tester), and

label: Body
text: will outline the benefits for companies that are considering the development of specific testing skills at this

label: H1
text: 2. Introduction to Foundation Level Agile Tester Extension

label: Body
text: The certification for Foundation Level Extension –  Agile Tester is designed for professionals who are

label: Body
text: working within Agile environments. It is also for professionals who are planning to start implementing

label: Body
text: Agile methods in the near future, or are working within companies that plan to do so, The certification

label: Body
text: provides an advantage for those who would like to know the required Agile activities, roles, methods, and

label: Body
text: The Foundation Level Extension –  Agile Tester qualification is aimed at four main groups of professionals:

label: Body
text: 1. Professionals who have achieved in-depth testing experience in traditional methods and would

label: Body
text: like to get an Agile Tester Certificate.

label: Body
text: 2. Junior professional testers who are just starting in the testing profession, have received the

label: Body
text: Foundation Level certificate, and would like to know more about  the  tester’s  role in an Agile

label: Body
text: 3. Professionals who are relatively new to testing and are required to implement test approaches,

label: Body
text: methods and techniques in their day to day job in Agile projects.

label: Body
text: 4. Professionals who are experienced in their role (including unit testing) and need more

label: Body
text: understanding and knowledge about how to perform and manage testing on all levels in Agile

label: Body
text: These professionals include people who are in roles such as testers, test analysts, test engineers, test

label: Body
text: consultants, test managers, user acceptance testers, and software developers.

label: Body
text: This Foundation Level Extension –  Agile Tester certification may also be appropriate for anyone who

label: Body
text: wants a deeper understanding of software testing in the Agile world, such as project managers, quality

label: Body
text: managers, software development managers, business analysts, IT directors, and management

label: Body
text: Building on the Foundation Level, the Agile Tester Extension supports the definition of career paths for

label: Body
text: professional testers. A person with the Agile Tester certificate has extended the broad understanding of

label: Body
text: testing acquired at the Foundation Level to enable him or her to work effectively as a professional tester in

label: Body
text: People possessing an ISTQB Foundation Level Extension –  Agile Tester certificate may use the Certified

label: Body
text: In general, the Foundation Level syllabus is examinable at a K1 level, i.e., the candidate will recognize,

label: Body
text: remember and recall terms and concepts stated in the Foundation Level syllabus.

label: Body
text: In addition, all Foundation Level syllabus learning objectives are examinable at the same K- level in an

label: Body
text: That said, each extension level exam focuses on the learning objectives defined in that extension

label: Body
text: syllabus. The relevant learning objectives at K1, K2, and K3 levels are provided at the beginning of each

label: Body
text: chapter within each particular extension syllabus.

label: Body
text: To be able to participate in a Foundation Level Extension –  Agile Tester exam, candidates must have

label: Body
text: obtained the ISTQB Foundation Level certificate.

label: H1
text: 3. Overview of the Foundation Level Extension –  Agile Tester

label: Body
text: This section lists the Business Outcomes expected of a candidate who has achieved the Foundation Level

label: Body
text: Collaborate in a cross-functional Agile team being familiar with principles and basic

label: Body
text: Adapt existing testing experience and knowledge to Agile values and principles.

label: Body
text: Support the Agile team in planning test-related activities.

label: Body
text: Apply relevant methods and techniques for testing in an Agile project.

label: Body
text: Assist the Agile team in test automation activities.

label: Body
text: Assist business stakeholders in defining understandable and testable user stories,

label: Body
text: scenarios, requirements and acceptance criteria as appropriate.

label: Body
text: Work and share information with other team members using effective communication

label: Body
text: In general, a Certified Tester Foundation Level –  Agile Tester is expected to have acquired the necessary

label: Body
text: skills to working effectively within an Agile team and environment.

label: Body
text: The tester should remember the basic concept of Agile software development based on the Agile

label: Body
text: The tester should understand the advantages of the whole-team approach and the benefits of

label: Body
text: The tester should recall Agile software development approaches.

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to write testable user stories in collaboration with developers and

label: Body
text: The tester should understand how retrospectives can be used as a mechanism for process

label: Body
text: The tester should understand the use and purpose of continuous integration.

label: Body
text: The tester should know the differences between iteration and release planning, and how a tester

label: Body
text: adds value in each of these activities.

label: Body
text: Chapter 2: Fundamental Agile Testing Principles, Practices, and Processes

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to describe the differences between testing activities in Agile projects

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to describe how development and testing activities are integrated in

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to describe the role of independent testing in Agile projects.

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to describe the tools and techniques used to communicate the status of

label: Body
text: testing in an Agile project, including test progress and product quality.

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to describe the process of evolving tests across multiple iterations and

label: Body
text: explain why test automation is important to manage regression risk in Agile projects.

label: Body
text: The tester should understand the skills (people, domain, and testing) of a tester in an Agile team.

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to understand the role of a tester within an Agile team.

label: Body
text: Chapter 3: Agile Testing Methods, Techniques, and Tools

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to recall the concepts of test-driven development, acceptance test-

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to recall the concepts of the test pyramid.

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to summarize the testing quadrants and their relationships with testing

label: Body
text: For a given Agile project, the tester should be able to work as a tester in a Scrum team.

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to assess quality risks within an Agile project.

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to estimate testing effort based on iteration content and quality risks.

text: The tester should be able to explain to business stakeholders how to define testable acceptance

text: For both functional and non-functional behavior, the tester should be able to write test cases using

label: Body
text: black box test design techniques based on given user stories.

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to perform exploratory testing to support the testing of an Agile project.

label: Body
text: The tester should be able to recall different tools available to testers according to their purpose

label: Body
text: First, some background on the ODL. For the last two years the Ontario Library Association

label: Body
text: has acted as a catalyst, bringing together the stakeholders needed to create the Ontario

label: Body
text: Digital Library (ODL). These stakeholders include Ontario’s 5000+ public libraries, university,

label: Body
text: college, and school libraries, as well as Ontario government ministries.

label: Body
text: Libraries that serve very different clientele recognize that by working together they can create

label: Body
text: seamless access to quality electronic library services. Through the ODL, students will be

label: Body
text: able to explore a topic at school, use the same child-safe resources after school (either at

label: Body
text: home or at a public library), enter college or university with a knowledge of how to use

label: Body
text: electronic resources that are still available and then, after graduation, continue to use these

label: Body
text: skills and resources at work or at home.

label: Body
text: We are moving into a period of convergence. With convergence we no longer have to license

label: Body
text: commercial products as individual libraries or institutions. We can work together to spend our

label: Body
text: money wisely. The provincial government has made this possible by working hard to provide

label: Body
text: all Ontarians with a stable, high-speed communications infrastructure. While there is still a

label: Body
text: great deal of work needed to improve this infrastructure, libraries are beginning to plan how

label: Body
text: best to exploit communications technology. We can reduce barriers to access and create the

label: Body
text: content infrastructure needed to support a knowledge society.

label: Body
text: The concept of an ODL is a key element in The Roadmap to Prosperity , a strategic plan to

label: Body
text: envision and attain Ontario’s economic goal prepared by the Ontario Jobs and Investment

label: Body
text: Board. The OJIB strategic plan recommends an electronic library to “connect students to new

label: Body
text: workplaces, new sources of information and applied learning opportunities”. The ODL will do

label: Body
text: that and much more. The ODL will connect students to electronic information, and will also

label: Body
text: leverage this investment to help connect all citizens to the electronic information they need as

label: Body
text: they make decisions, solve problems and enhance their quality of life.

label: Body
text: Libraries have long been a key delivery point for public services. The ODL will allow that

label: Body
text: delivery point to move closer to citizens, into the smallest of libraries and even into living

label: Body
text: Libraries have a long tradition of using a practical, consultative approach to solving problems,

label: Body
text: and of learning from others. The ODL is a very practical solution to various problems.

label: Body
text: Jurisdiction-wide digital libraries are very practical and very real. The ODL we propose is

label: Body
text: leading edge for Ontario but several jurisdictions have forged the path with collaborative

label: Body
text: digital libraries. We can learn from their experiences. For example, The Alberta Library (TAL)

label: Other
text: RFP: To Develop the Ontario Digital Library Business Plan

label: Body
text: was incorporated in 1997 as a province-wide library consortium. TAL works collaboratively

label: Body
text: with its members to promote universal access to materials and resources in more than 250

label: Body
text: public, post-secondary, special, government and regional libraries. Unlike ODL, TAL does

label: Body
text: not include elementary or secondary schools. However, the timeline and funding we are

label: Body
text: proposing for ODL is comparable to TAL‘s experience. TAL’s business planning took several

label: Body
text: years. TAL’s implementation plan was supported by 8 million dollars in provincially shared

label: Body
text: funding, spread over three years, later revised to 15 million dollars over 4 years. Not only is

label: Body
text: Alberta’s population 30% of Ontario’s, TAL does not include elementary or secondary

label: Body
text: schools as partners; it has 250 member libraries. ODL envisions universal access for all

label: Body
text: 10,000,000 Ontarians, with more than 5000 Ontario libraries as partners. Although ODL can

label: Body
text: learn from TAL’s practices, the scope of planning and implementing ODL is much larger than

label: Body
text: The ODL will be a partnership-based organization providing seamless electronic information

label: Body
text: services and resources to the citizens of Ontario. It will use local libraries as the entry point for

label: Body
text: common resources The ODL will recognize the unique responsibilities and needs of public

label: Body
text: libraries, school libraries, college and university libraries and special libraries. The ODL

label: Body
text: envisions a digital network of information resources, allowing members to collaborate when

label: Body
text: there is mutual benefit and to support the common mandates of local libraries.

label: Body
text: The principles which will define and guide the ODL are:

label: Body
text: We will bring consistent, high-quality electronic resources and services to 10 million

label: Body
text: We will eliminate barriers to the access to information and create more consistent

label: Body
text: We will facilitate consensus among members regarding ODL’s portfolio of electronic

label: Body
text: We will balance the interests and realities of small and large as well as rich and poor

label: Body
text: We will share decision-making in order to enable the people we serve.

label: Body
text: We will work based on an underlying assumption of trust and synergy.

label: Body
text: We will leverage provincial, institutional, and local dollars to realize economies of scale

label: Body
text: and put Ontario dollars to work for everyone .

label: Body
text: We will be willing to pool talents and dollars in order to provide common services that are

label: Body
text: truly greater than those that can be maintained by individual institutions.

text: RFP: To Develop the Ontario Digital Library Business Plan

label: Body
text: We will provide the licenses, infrastructure, services and support that enable local

label: Body
text: libraries to provide exceptional services to their clientele. ODL will focus on support,

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body
text: output  quality  using  both  reference  and  blind  (no-reference)  metrics.

label: Body

text: Crop  high-resolution  images  into  patches  (e.g.,  512×512  pixels).

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

text: For  dual-image  input,  modify  the  model  to  accept  and  fuse  features  from  both  images.

label: H1
text: HOW TO READ AN ANALYTICAL METHOD

label: Body
text: The procedure for a particular experiment states “make up a series of standards from your

label: Body
text: stock solution, from X to Y concentration.” How do you proceed?

label: Body
text: There are several important pieces of information hidden in the above instructions.

label: Body
text: 1. “make up … from your stock solution”:  all of your standards will originate from

label: Body
text: this solution.  In some cases, where a wide range of concentrations is required, you

label: Body
text: may need to prepare a ‘sub-stock’ solution (diluted stock), which you will then use

label: Body
text: to make your most dilute standards.

label: Body
text: 2. “a series of standards”:  in some cases you will be told to make a certain number of

label: Body
text: standards; in others it is left to your discretion. Generally, four or five standards

label: Body
text: are used to prepare a calibration curve. You must prepare at least three standards.

label: Body
text: 3. “standards … from X to Y”:  this is the concentration range that your standards

label: Body
text: will cover.  Your most dilute standard will have a concentration of X.  Your most

label: Body
text: concentrated standard will have a concentration of Y.  Units will depend on the

label: Body
text: 4. the dilutions you use to make your standards must be calculated to ‘fit’ the

label: Body
text: glassware available.  You will have access to 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 25 and 50 mL

label: Body
text: volumetric pipettes.  You also have 25, 50, 100, 200, 250, 500 and 1000 mL

label: Body
text: volumetric flasks.  Calculate your dilutions so they ‘fit’ this equipment. (e.g., 1.5

label: Body

label: Body
text: A chemical laboratory is a potentially dangerous environment; the hazards of fire, cuts, burns

label: Body
text: and poisoning being most prevalent.  It is a safe practice to assume all chemical reagents are

label: Body
text: potentially hazardous.  While the use of particularly toxic or carcinogenic reagents is generally

label: Body
text: avoided, some of the reagents in this lab are dangerous.  Check the MSDS and consult your

label: Body
text: instructor for more information.  The first line of defence for skin contact is to flush with plenty

label: Body
text: of water.  Two eyewash stations are provided for the immediate flushing of eye splashes.  In the

label: Body
text: event of an accident, contact your instructor immediately.  Safety rules will work only if you

label: Body
text: obey them and encourage others to obey them.  Please familiarise yourself with the following

label: Body
text: There must be no smoking or eating in the laboratory.

label: Body
text: Students must wear safety glasses at all times.  Safety glasses are available.  Contact lenses

label: Body
text: should be removed prior to entering the laboratory.  Prescription glasses may be worn, but

label: Body
text: should be covered with safety glasses.

label: Body
text: Students are recommended to wear laboratory coats in the laboratory.

label: Body
text: Many of the chemicals in the laboratory are poisonous whether taken orally or absorbed

label: Body
text: through the skin.  If any chemical is swallowed the supervisor should be summoned

label: Body
text: immediately.  If any chemical comes into contact with the skin it should be washed off

label: Body
text: While heating a substance in a test tube, care should be taken to ensure that the mouth of the

label: Body
text: test tube is not pointing at anyone.  A student should never look down into a test tube that is

label: Body
text: Concentrated acids and bases; strong oxidising and reducing agents; flammable solvents and

label: Body
text: toxic chemicals should be treated with respect.

label: Body
text: Always wash your hands prior to existing the lab and before eating.

label: Body
text: In the event of fire, the flames should be extinguished with one of the extinguishers in the

label: Body
text: laboratory and the supervisor notified immediately.

label: Body
text: All breakages and minor spills of chemicals should be reported immediately to the supervisor

text: The following notes on proper experimental technique and use of equipment are collectively

label: Body
text: known as GLPs. It is assumed that the student is familiar with and always practices the following

label: Body
text: procedures outlined in this section.  Your laboratory instructor will be evaluating your experimental

label: Body
text: technique. Failure to practice the following will lead to poor results and poor technique. Both of

label: Body
text: these are graded. Exceptions to standard GLPs must be noted in your lab report.

label: Body
text: Care must be taken to ensure that glassware is thoroughly clean before use.  However, recognize

label: Body
text: that soap can be a serious chemical contaminant.  Do not clean your glassware with soap unless

label: Body
text: specifically instructed.  In general, glassware will be supplied clean, acid washed and thoroughly

label: Body
text: rinsed with deionized water. Properly cleaned glassware is indicated by the presence of an

label: Body
text: unbroken film of water on the surface.  It is seldom necessary to dry glassware before use; in fact

label: Body
text: this practice should be discouraged because it wastes time, can be a cause of contamination and

label: Body
text: result in changes in volumetric glassware.

label: Body
text: Always pre-rinse burets and volumetric pipettes with the titrant or solution to be transferred prior

label: Body
text: to use.  Note that rinsing is most effectively accomplished with a greater number of small

label: Body
text: portions, rather than a smaller number of large portions.

label: Body
text: Rinse all glassware with tap and distilled water after use. Never let reagents dry in volumetric

label: Body
text: Good housekeeping is important for the safety and convenience of everyone, including the

label: Body
text: cleaning staff, who are not chemists.  The analytical lab is a shared space.  It is a busy place, and

label: Body
text: any mess you don't clean up will inconvenience many people.  A mess will not impress your lab

label: Body
text: instructor and you certainly won't impress any future employers with poor, unsafe work habits.

label: Body
text: Don't leave equipment and chemicals scattered over the benchtop; return them when you are

label: Body
text: finished using them.  This allows others to use the same equipment, and prevents any accidents

label: Body
text: involving or resulting from your mess.  Fumehood space is often at a premium, so clear out as

label: Body
text: soon as you no longer need to work there.  When you are finished working, in the fumehood

label: Body
text: especially, clean the entire area with a damp paper towel.  Clean up all chemical spills

label: Body
text: immediately, especially when the balances or other instruments are involved.  Wash the outside

label: Body
text: of reagent bottles when you are finished using them.  Drips and small spills may go unnoticed

label: Body
text: until they have had some time to react and cause a burn, at which point it is too late.

label: Body
text: Never leave experiments unattended.  If you must, especially in the case of reactions and

label: Body
text: digestions or anything that involves the use of hotplates and stirrers, inform your lab instructor

label: Body
text: and have them or another student keep an eye on your experiment.  Even if you have to leave the

label: Body
text: lab for only a minute to go to the bathroom, inform your lab instructor.

label: Body
text: When using chemicals and supplies, use all of one container before opening another one, unless

label: Body
text: specifically directed to do otherwise by your lab instructor.  Inform your lab instructor of any

label: Body
text: chemicals or supplies that are running low, including cylinders of compressed gases and printer

label: Body
text: supplies, so that there will be enough for the next student to complete their experiment.  Also

label: Body
text: inform your lab instructor as soon as possible if anything is missing or if anything is broken, so

label: Body
text: that replacements can be obtained as quickly as possible.

label: Body
text: Dispose of all refuse in the appropriate waste container as soon as possible; if in doubt ask your

label: Body
text: lab instructor.  Questions are not ‘stupid’; unlike endangering the lives and health of others.  At

label: Body
text: the end of the lab, return all chemicals and equipment where they belong and clean up your work

label: Body
text: area.  Double-check everywhere you worked, make sure that all equipment and supplies are

label: Body
text: returned, and all waste appropriately disposed (including any bench and fumehood space, the

label: Body
text: balances, instruments and sinks where you worked).  As far as possible, shut down and turn off

label: Body
text: all equipment that you have worked with as soon as you have finished.

text: Remove the funnel while rinsing the stem into the flask.

label: Body
text: Most solids absorb atmospheric moisture and, as a consequence, change in composition.

label: Body
text: This effect can be substantial when a large surface area is exposed to a humid

label: Body
text: atmosphere, as with a reagent that is a fine powder.  It is ordinarily necessary to dry such

label: Body
text: solids before weighing to free the results from dependence upon the atmospheric

label: Body
text: humidity.  Oven drying is the most convenient method for removing absorbed moisture

label: Body
text: from a solid.  This technique, of course, is not appropriate for samples that change

label: Body
text: composition at the temperature of the oven.  Furthermore, with some solids the

label: Body
text: temperatures attainable in ordinary drying ovens are insufficient to completely remove

label: Body
text: While cooling, dried material is stored in a desiccator to prevent the uptake of

label: Body
text: atmospheric moisture.  The base of the desiccator contains a chemical drying agent.

label: Body
text: Samples are placed on a perforated plate that is supported by a constriction in the

label: Body
text: desiccator wall.  Lightly greased ground-glass surfaces provide a tight seal between the

label: Body
text: lid and the base of the desiccator.  Whether it is being replaced or removed, the lid of the

label: Body
text: desiccator is properly moved by a sliding, rather than a lifting, motion.  An airtight seal is

label: Body
text: achieved by slight rotation and direct downward pressure on the positioned lid.

label: Body
text: When handling heated objects manipulations should be practiced first, if necessary, to

label: Body
text: assure that adequate control can be maintained with the implements to be used.  If using

label: Body
text: tongs, always place them on surfaces so the grips are in the air rather than resting on the

label: Body
text: surface (prevents contamination).  When a heated object is placed in a desiccator, the

label: Body
text: increased pressure of the enclosed air may be sufficient to break the seal between the lid

label: Body
text: and the base, causing the lid to slide off and break.  Upon cooling, the opposite effect is

label: Body
text: likely to occur, the interior of the desiccator now being under a partial vacuum.  Both of

label: Body
text: these conditions can cause the contents of the desiccator to be physically lost or

label: Body
text: contaminated.  Although it defeats the purpose somewhat, it may be best to allow some

label: Body
text: cooling to occur before finally sealing the lid.  It also helps to break the seal several times

label: Body
text: during cooling to relieve any vacuum that may be forming.

text: Micropipettors are commercially available in various sizes; some deliver a fixed volume

label: Body
text: while others are adjustable within a given range. Common volumes for micropipettors in

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

text: If the reagent bottle is small and/or easy to handle, the amount of reagent required may be

label: Body

text: by Shelley Chang (appropriated by Lucas Garron)

label: Body
text: A letter by itself (e.g. F) means turn that face 90 degrees clockwise with respect to the center of the cube. A letter with an

label: Body
text: apostrophe (F') denotes a 90 degree counter-clockwise turn. A letter followed by the number 2 (F2) denotes 2 turns, i.e. a

label: Body
text: Your first objective is to solve the four white edges, building a cross on your first layer as shown below.

label: Body
text: Note that each white edge piece has another color sticker on it. When the white cross is completed, this other color has to

label: Body
text: match the center piece it's adjacent to.

label: H2
text: Your cross should look like this:

label: Body
text: Once you have finished the cross, keep the white cross on the bottom face for the rest of your solve.

label: Body
text: Your next step is to complete the first layer by filling in the corners. Locate a corner piece that has a white sticker on it.

label: Body
text: There are four of them, and they can be found on the top layer or bottom layer.

label: Body
text: If the corner piece is on the top layer, rotate U until it is directly above where it needs to go. Hold the cube so that this

label: Body
text: corner is at the UFR position. Now check the position of the white sticker. You have three possible cases:

label: Body
text: If the white corner piece is on the bottom layer, replace it with different corner piece from the top layer. The white corner

label: Body
text: piece will then be in the top layer and you can now deal with it using one of the cases indicated above.

label: Body
text: Once you have done this with all four corners, you should be done with the first layer.

label: Body
text: Notice that the middle layer consists of just four edge pieces that need to be solved. An easy way to identify a middle layer

label: Body
text: edge is to look for edge pieces that have no yellow stickers on it.

label: Body
text: If the middle layer edge is on the top layer, rotate U until it's matched with an adjacent center sticker. Hold the cube so that

label: Body
text: its target position (where you want to place that edge) is at the FR position. You have two possible cases:

label: Body
text: U R U' R' U' F' U F

label: Body
text: U' F' U F U R U' R'

label: Body
text: Once you're finished with all four middle layer edges, you are done with the first two layers.

label: Body
text: For the last layer, diagrams will show a top-down view of what your top layer looks like. You will still be executing the

label: Body
text: algorithms with the top layer as the U face.

label: Body
text: Your first objective is to orient the last layer edge pieces so they all have yellow facing up, forming a yellow cross on the

label: Body
text: last layer. The orientation of your last layer edges has three possible cases:

label: Body
text: F R U R' U' F'

label: Body
text: F U R U' R' F'

label: Body
text: Complete the last layer orientation by orienting the corners so that they all have yellow facing up. You only need to learn

label: Body
text: two algorithms for this. In fact, it's really only one algorithm, because one is simply the mirror image of the other. In the

label: Body
text: diagrams, the dashes on the sides represent which side the yellow sticker is on.

label: Body
text: Case 1: Exactly one corner is already correctly oriented (has yellow sticker on top). Determine which case it matches and

label: Body
text: R U R' U R U2 R'

label: Body
text: L' U' L U' L' U2 L

label: Body
text: Case 2: Exactly two corners are correctly oriented. Hold the cube so that the UFL corner needs to be rotated counter-

label: Body
text: clockwise (there should be a yellow sticker on the front face; see diagram) and do R U R' U R U2 R' to bring you to Case 1.

label: Body
text: Case 3: No corners are correctly oriented. Hold the cube so that the UFL corner needs to be rotated clockwise (there should

label: Body
text: be a yellow sticker on the left face; see diagram) and do R U R' U R U2 R' to bring you to Case 1.

label: Body
text: If you end up with exactly three corners correctly oriented, your cube is in an unsolvable state.

label: Body
text: You're almost done! Now all you have to do is position all the pieces where they need to go. Let's start with the corners.

label: Body
text: There's only one algorithm you need here, the two corner switch:

label: Body
text: R' F R' B2 R F' R' B2 R2 U'

label: Body
text: You may have to do this algorithm more than once (e.g. if two opposite corners need to be switched). Once all your corners

label: Body
text: are correctly positioned, you can move on to the edges:

label: Body
text: F2 U R' L F2 R L' U F2

label: Body
text: F2 U' R' L F2 R L' U' F2

label: Body
text: Note that these two algorithms are identical except for the direction in which to turn U. It's easy enough to remember: it's U

label: Body
text: to cycle edges clockwise and U' to cycle them counterclockwise.

label: Body
text: You may have four edges that need to be positioned, in which case do the 3 edge cycle twice as needed.

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body

label: Body
text: Solubility is defined as the maximum amount of solute that we can dissolve in any given solvent (yielding a

label: Body
text: saturated solution). It not only depends on the nature of solute and solvent but also on temperature and pressure.

label: H2
text: 3.1 Solubility of a Solid in Liquid

label: Body
text: Suppose that a solid solute is added continuously to a liquid solvent; then, the solute continues dissolving and

label: Body
text: consequently the concentration of the solution increases. We call this process as dissolution. However, ultimately, a

label: Body
text: state is reached where no more solute dissolves at the given temperature. This is basically because of the fact that

label: Body
text: from the solution, the solute particles keep on colliding on the surface of solid solute particles and ultimately get

label: Body
text: separated out of the solution. This process is known as crystallization. Thereafter, no more solute particles dissolve

label: Body
text: because the rate of dissolution equalizes the rate of crystallization, i.e., a dynamic equilibrium is attained.

label: Body
text: Further, the solution at this stage is said to be a saturated solution. However, an unsaturated solution is one in

label: Body
text: which more solute particles dissolve at the same temperature. Thus, the concentration of such a saturated solution

label: Body
text: is called its ‘solubility.’ Now, as per our discussion so far in this regard, we define solubility as follows:

label: Body
text: The solubility of a solid in a liquid at any temperature is defined as the maximum amount of the solid

label: Body
text: (solute) in grams which can dissolve in 100g of the liquid (solvent) to form the saturated solution at that

label: Body
text: Factors affecting solubility of a solid in a liquid

label: Body
text: (a)	 Nature of Solute and Solvent: Generally, a solid dissolves in a liquid which is chemically similar to it. We

label: Body
text: can say this conveniently as ‘like dissolves like.’ In this regard, ionic compounds usually get dissolved in polar

label: Body
text: solvents, whereas covalent compounds are soluble in non-polar solvents.

label: Body
text: Explanation: For ionic compounds that are being dissolved in polar solvents, the solubility is due to the fact that

label: Body
text: there are strong electrostatic forces of attraction between the ions of the crystal and the polar solvent molecules

label: Body
text: with the negative ions being attracted with the positive poles of the solvent molecule and positive ions by negative

label: Body
text: poles. However, in case of water molecule, the situation can be represented as

label: Other
text: Figure 20.1: Dissociation of an ionic compound, like Na + Cl ‒ , in a polar solvent (H 2 O)

label: Body
text: Thus, the water molecules pull apart the ions of the crystal and the electrostatic forces of attraction between the

label: Body
text: ions of the crystal are hence cut off. Further, we observe that the ions are surrounded by the water molecules which

label: Body
text: act as a sheath (or envelope) around the ions and hence prevent the possible recombination of the ions. Such ions

label: Body
text: that are thus moving freely in the solution are said to be hydrated. It is to be noted here that whereas energy is

label: Body
text: required for the splitting of the ionic compound into ions (called lattice energy), energy is released when the ions

label: Body
text: get hydrated (called hydration energy). It follows then that a substance dissolves if its hydration energy is greater

label: Body
text: than its lattice energy, i.e., D hyd H > D lattice H.

label: Body
text: It may be further mentioned here that whereas water is the best polar solvent (having the highest dielectric constant),

label: Body
text: liquid ammonia, liquid hydrogen sulfide and liquid sulfur dioxide are also good solvents for ionic compounds.

label: Body
text: In the case of non-polar compounds being dissolved in non-polar solvents, the solubility principle is due to similar

label: Body
text: (b)	 Temperature: The solubility of solutes is generally dependent on temperature. For example, when a solid

label: Body
text: dissolves in a liquid, a change in the physical state of the solid, analogous to melting, takes place. However,

label: Body
text: heat is required to break the bonds holding the molecules in the solid together. On the contrary, heat is

label: Body
text: liberated during the formation of new solute–solvent bonds.

label: Body
text: If ∆ H solution < 0, i.e., (–ve), then the dissolution is exothermic. In this case, as the temperature increases,

label: Body
text: If ∆ H solution > 0, i.e., (+ve), then there is endothermic dissolution. In this case, increase in temperature

label: H2
text: 3.2 Solubility of a Gas in a Liquid

label: Body
text: The solubility of any gas in a particular liquid is the volume of the gas in cc (converted to STP) that can dissolve in

label: Body
text: unit volume (1 cc) of the liquid to form the saturated solution at the temperature of the experiment and under a

label: Body
text: pressure of one atmosphere. This method helps us to express the concentration as an absorption coefficient of the

label: Body
text: gas and is usually represent by α .

label: Body
text: Further, solubility of a gas in a liquid at a particular temperature is also expressed in terms of molarity (moles of

label: Body
text: the gas dissolved per liter of the solvent to form the saturated solution, i.e., in terms of mol L –1 ) or in terms of mole

label: Body
text: (a)	 Nature of the gas and solvent: It is to be noted here that gases like H 2 , O 2 , N 2 , etc. dissolve in water only

label: Body
text: to a small extent, whereas gases such as CO 2 , HCl and NH 3 are highly soluble. However, the greater solubility

label: Body
text: pattern of the latter gases is mainly due to their reaction with the solvent or chemical similarity.

label: Body
text: (b)	 Effect of Temperature: The solubility nature of gases decreases with an increase in temperature as dissolution

label: Body
text: is an exothermic process, i.e., it is accompanied by evolution of heat. Thus

label: Body
text: By applying Le Chatelier’s principle, it is clearly evident that increase of temperature would shift the equilibrium

label: Body
text: in the backward direction, i.e., the solubility would decrease.

label: Body
text: Exceptions – The  solubility of some sparingly soluble gases, such as hydrogen and inert gases, increases

label: Body
text: slightly with increase of temperature especially in the case of non-aqueous solvents such as hydrocarbons,

label: Body
text: (c)	 Effect of Pressure (Henry’s law): As the pressure increases, the solubility also increases. We explain this

label: Body
text: concept using the following example. As an example

label: Body
text: of a solution of a gas in a liquid, consider a system

label: Body
text: as shown in Fig. 2 (a). In this figure, the lower part

label: Body
text: is the solution, whereas the upper part is gaseous

label: Body
text: at pressure p and temperature T. Now, let us

label: Body
text: suppose that the system is in dynamic equilibrium,

label: Body
text: i.e., rate of gaseous particles entering and leaving

label: Body
text: the solution is the same, which means that rate of

label: Body
text: dissolution = rate of evaporation. Now, let us

label: Body
text: increase the pressure over the system as shown in

label: Body
text: Fig. 2 (b). Consequently, the gas gets compressed

label: Body
text: on solubility of a gas in liquid

label: Body
text: to a smaller volume. Due to this effect, the total

label: Body
text: number of gaseous particles per unit volume tends to increase. Because of this, the total number of gaseous

label: Body
text: particles striking at the surface of the solution and hence entering into it also increases. The process is

label: Body
text: continuous till a new equilibrium is reestablished. Thus, we learn that upon increase of the pressure of the gas

label: Body
text: above the solution, the solubility also increases.

label: Body
text: Quantitatively, this fact was also explained by Henry’s law which states that the solubility of a gas in a liquid is

label: Body
text: directly proportional to the pressure of the gas over the solution at a definite temperature.

label: Body
text: In this regard, Dalton also concluded independently that, if a mixture of gases is simultaneously is in equilibrium

label: Body
text: with the liquid at a particular temperature, then the solubility of any gas in the mixture is directly proportional

label: Body
text: to the partial pressure of that gas in the mixture.

label: Body
text: By expressing solubility in terms of mole fraction of the gas in the solution, for a gas A, Henry’s law can be

label: Other
text: written as X A = K ′ P A

label: Other
text: However, this can also be written as:

label: Body
text: Henry’s law is applicable only when

label: Body
text: The pressure of the gas is not too high and temperature is not too low.
